lbum)|Allies]]'' (CSN) (live and studio)\n* 1988 ''[[American Dream (Crosby, Stills, Nash & Young album)|American Dream]]'' (CSNY)\n* 1990 ''[[Live It Up (Crosby, Stills & Nash album)|Live It Up]]'' (CSN)\n* 1994 ''[[After the Storm (Crosby, Stills & Nash album)|After the Storm]]'' (CSN)\n* 1999 ''[[Looking Forward]]'' (CSNY) \n* 2008 ''[[D\u00e9j\u00e0 Vu Live]]'' (CSNY) (live)\n\n== Tours ==\n{{Importance section|date=February 2020}}\n{{Prose|section|date=February 2020}}\n\nSee: [[Crosby, Stills, Nash and Young 1969-1970 Tours]]\n\nCrosby, Stills, & Nash have done 29 tours; sometimes with Neil Young. Their first tour was as CSNY, and was a four-leg, 39-date tour that started  on August 16, 1969, at the [[Auditorium Theatre]] in Chicago, with [[Joni Mitchell]] as their opening act. Their second gig was a one-hour show at the [[Woodstock|Woodstock Festival]] in the early morning of August 18, 1969. During that tour they also appeared at the [[Big Sur Folk Festival]] (September 13\u201314, 1969), and the notorious [[Altamont Free Concert]] on December 6, 1969.  The tour ended with three European concerts in January 1970.  They were accompanied on the tour by [[Greg Reeves]] on bass, and [[Dallas Taylor (drummer)| Dallas Taylor]] on drums. \n\nBefore the start of their second tour, Greg Reeves was replaced on bass by Calvin Samuels. The tour is notorious for the tensions within the band, and Dallas Taylor was fired, to be replaced by  [[John Barbata]] on drums, and Stephen Stills was temporarily sacked by the rest of the group. The tour started in Denver Coliseum on 12 May 1970, and finished after 22 dates at the [[Met Center]] in [[Bloomington, Minnesota]] on 9 July 1970, after which the group split up. The double live album ''[[4 Way Street]]'', released April 1971, was recorded at several dates on this tour.  \n\n\n'''[[CSNY 1974|1974 So Far Tour]]'''\n*Bass: [[Tim Drummond]]; Drums: [[Russ Kunkel]]; Percussion: [[Joe Lala]]\n'''[[CSN (album)|1977 CSN Tour]]'''\n*K